          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>As in <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.6" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.6.xml" number="5.1.6" />, we define the topos of <fr:em>sheaves</fr:em> on an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>-simplicial topological space.
    Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ^\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be the functor
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       F       \mapsto  (\Gamma (X_{n_1\ldots  n_r},F^{n_1\ldots  n_r}))     ]]></fr:tex>
    from sheaves on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>-cosimplicial sets.
    For small <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>, we often prefer to write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ^{\bullet \ldots \bullet }]]></fr:tex> (with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>-many copies of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bullet ]]></fr:tex>).
    We have a co-augmentation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma (X_\bullet ,F^\bullet )\to \Gamma ^\bullet (X_\bullet ,F^\bullet )]]></fr:tex>.
    The functors of <fr:em>cohomology with values in an abelian sheaf <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex></fr:em> are the derived functors of the "global sections" functor <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex>.
    They can be calculated by a procedure parallel to that of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.xml" number="5.2.3" />, i.e.

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2259</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-6.4.2.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-6.4.2.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>6.4.2.1</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-6.4.2</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \mathrm {R}\Gamma          =\mathrm {s}\mathrm {R}\Gamma ^\bullet          \colon  \mathrm {D}^+(X_\bullet )         \to \mathrm {D}^+((\mathsf {Ab})).       \tag{6.4.2.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
            <fr:p>A sheaf <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> on an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>-simplicial topological space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> induces a sheaf <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta  F]]></fr:tex> on the diagonal simplicial space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta  X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>.
    It follows from the Cartier–Eilenberg–Zilber theorem that

